Termites were previously regarded as a separate order [[Isoptera]] to cockroaches. However, recent genetic evidence strongly suggests that they evolved directly from 'true' cockroaches, and many authors now place them as an "[[epifamily]]" of Blattodea.<ref name="Eggleton, P. 2007"/> This evidence supported a hypothesis suggested in 1934 that termites are closely related to the wood-eating cockroaches (genus ''[[Cryptocercus]]''). This hypothesis was originally based on similarity of the symbiotic gut [[flagellate]]s in termites regarded as [[living fossil]]s and wood-eating cockroaches.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cleveland |first1=L.R. |last2=Hall |first2=S.K.|last3=Sanders |first3=E.P. |last4=Collier |first4=J. |title=The Wood-Feeding Roach ''Cryptocercus'', Its Protozoa, and the Symbiosis between Protozoa and Roach |journal=Memoirs of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences |date=1934 |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=185–382 |doi=10.1093/aesa/28.2.216}}</ref> Additional evidence emerged when F.&nbsp;A. McKittrick (1965) noted similar morphological characteristics between some termites and cockroach nymphs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McKittrick |first1=F.A. |title=A contribution to the understanding of cockroach-termite affinities |journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America |year=1965 |volume=58 |issue=1 |pages=18–22 |doi=10.1093/aesa/58.1.18 |pmid=5834489}}</ref> The similarities among these cockroaches and termites have led some scientists to reclassify termites as a single family, the Termitidae, within the order Blattodea.<ref name="Eggleton, P. 2007"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eggleton |first1=Paul |last2=Beccaloni |first2=George |last3=Inward |first3=Daegan |title=Response to Lo et al. |journal=Biology Letters |date=2007 |volume=3 |issue=5 |pages=564–565 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2007.0367|pmc=2391203 }}</ref> Other scientists have taken a more conservative approach, proposing to retain the termites as the Termitoidea, an [[epifamily]] within the order. Such measure preserves the classification of termites at family level and below.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lo |first1=Nathan |last2=Engel |first2=Michael S. |last3=Cameron |first3=Stephen |last4=Nalepa |first4=Christine A. |last5=Tokuda |first5=Gaku |last6=Grimaldi |first6=David |last7=Kitade |first7=Osamu |last8=Krishna|first8=Kumar |last9=Klass |first9=Klaus-Dieter |last10=Maekawa |first10=Kiyoto |last11=Miura |first11=Toru |last12=Thompson |first12=Graham J. |title=Comment. Save Isoptera: A comment on Inward et al.|journal=Biology Letters |year=2007 |volume=3 |issue=5 |pages=562–563 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2007.0264 |pmid=17698448 |pmc=2391185}}</ref>

==Description==
[[File:Domino cockroach Therea petiveriana.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Domino cockroach ''Therea petiveriana'', normally found in [[India]]]]
Most species of cockroach are about the size of a thumbnail, but several species are bigger. The world's heaviest cockroach is the Australian [[giant burrowing cockroach]] ''Macropanesthia rhinoceros'', which can reach {{convert|9|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length and weigh more than {{convert|30|g|oz|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pet facts: giant burrowing cockroaches |url=http://www.abc.net.au/creaturefeatures/facts/cockroach.htm |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=3 December 2005}}</ref> Comparable in size is the Central American giant cockroach ''[[Blaberus giganteus]]'', which grows to a similar length.<ref name=Huang>{{cite journal | last1 = Huang | first1 = C.Y. | last2 = Sabree | first2 = Z.L. | last3 = Moran | first3 = N.A. | year = 2012 | title = Genome Sequence of ''Blattabacterium'' sp. Strain BGIGA, Endosymbiont of the ''Blaberus giganteus'' Cockroach | journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 194 | issue = 16| pages = 4450–4451 | doi=10.1128/jb.00789-12| pmid = 22843586 | pmc=3416254}}</ref> The longest cockroach species is ''[[Megaloblatta longipennis]]'', which can reach {{convert|97|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|45|mm|in|abbr=on}} across.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-cockroach/ |title=Guinness World Records: World's Largest Cockroach |author=Guinness World Records |date= }}</ref> A Central and South American species, ''[[Megaloblatta blaberoides]]'', has the largest wingspan of up to {{convert|185|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/about-us/news/2006/may/news_8129.html |title=Natural History Museum: Cockroaches hit the shelves |publisher=Natural History Museum |date=May 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819141741/http://www.nhm.ac.uk/about-us/news/2006/may/news_8129.html |archivedate=19 August 2006 |accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Cockroach head.jpg|thumb|upright|Head of ''[[Periplaneta americana]]'']]

Cockroaches are generalized insects, with few special adaptations, and may be among the most [[Primitive (phylogenetics)|primitive]] living [[neoptera]]n insects. They have a relatively small head and a broad, flattened body, and most species are reddish-brown to dark brown. They have large [[compound eye]]s, two [[ocelli]], and long, flexible [[antenna (biology)|antennae]]. The [[Mandible (arthropod mouthpart)|mouthparts]] are on the underside of the head and include generalized chewing [[mandible (arthropod mouthpart)|mandibles]], [[salivary gland]]s and various touch and taste receptors.<ref name=ISC>{{cite web |url=http://biology4isc.weebly.com/7-morphology-and-anatomy-of-cockroach.html |title=Diversity of Life: Cockroach anatomy |work=Biology4ISC |accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>

The body is divided into a thorax of three segments and a ten-segmented abdomen. The external surface has a tough [[exoskeleton]] which contains [[calcium carbonate]] and protects the inner organs and provides attachment to muscles. It is coated with wax to repel water. The wings are attached to the second and third thoracic segments. The [[Tegmen|tegmina]], or first pair of wings, are tough and protective, lying as a shield on top of the membranous hind wings, which are used in flight. All four wings have branching longitudinal veins, and multiple cross-veins.<ref name=IIBD>{{cite book |author1=Hoell, H. V. |author2=Doyen, J. T. |author3=Purcell, A. H. |year=1998 |title=Introduction to Insect Biology and Diversity |edition=2nd |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=362–364 |isbn=0-19-510033-6}}</ref>

The three pairs of legs are sturdy, with large [[Arthropod leg|coxae]] and five claws each.<ref name=IIBD/> They are attached to each of the three thoracic segments. The front legs are the shortest and the hind legs the longest, providing the main propulsive power when the insect runs.<ref name=ISC/> The spines on the legs were earlier considered to be sensory, but observations of the insect's gait on sand and wire meshes have demonstrated that they help in locomotion on difficult terrain. The structures have been used as inspiration for robotic legs.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.asd.2004.05.001 | last1=Ritzmann | first1=Roy E. | last2=Quinn | first2=Roger D. | last3=Fischer | first3=Martin S. | year=2004 | title=Convergent evolution and locomotion through complex terrain by insects, vertebrates and robots | url=http://www.case.edu/artsci/biol/ritzmann/Ritzmann%204.pdf | journal=Arthropod Structure & Development | volume=33 | issue=3 | pages=361–379}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1088/1748-3182/2/1/002 | last1=Spagna | first1=J.C. | last2=Goldman | first2=D.I. | last3=Lin | first3=P-C. | last4=Koditschek | first4=D.E. | last5=Full | first5=Robert J. | year=2007 | title=Distributed mechanical feedback control of rapid running on challenging terrain | journal=Bioinspiration & Biomimetics | volume=2 | issue=1 | pages=9–18 | pmid=17671322}}</ref>

The abdomen has ten segments, each with a pair of [[spiracle]]s for respiration. Segment ten bears a pair of [[Cercus|cerci]], a pair of anal styles, the anus and the external genitalia. Males have an [[aedeagus]] through which they secrete sperm during copulation and females have [[spermatheca]]e for storing sperm and an [[ovipositor]] through which the [[ootheca]] is laid.<ref name=ISC/>

==Distribution and habitat==
Cockroaches are abundant throughout the world and live in a wide range of environments, especially in the tropics and subtropics.<ref name="Meyer">{{cite web |last1=Meyer |first1=J. |title=Blattodea |url=https://www.cals.ncsu.edu/course/ent425/library/compendium/blattodea.html |work=General Entomology |publisher=University of North Carolina |accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> Cockroaches can withstand extremely cold temperatures, allowing them to live in the [[Arctic]]. Some species are capable of surviving temperatures of −188&nbsp;°F (−122&nbsp;°C) by manufacturing an antifreeze made out of [[glycerol]].<ref name="Mohs_McGee_2007">{{cite book |last1=Mohs |first1=K. |last2=McGee |first2=I. |title=Animal planet: the most extreme bugs |year=2007 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-0-7879-8663-6 |page=35 |edition=1st}}</ref> In [[North America]], 50 species separated into five families are found throughout the continent.<ref name="Meyer"/> 450 species are found in [[Australia]].<ref name=assu>{{cite web |title=Cockroaches: Order Blattodea |url=http://australianmuseum.net.au/cockroaches-order-blattodea|publisher=Australian Museum |accessdate=November 10, 2015|date=January 13, 2012}}</ref> Only about four widespread species are commonly regarded as pests.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Valles | first1=S. M. | last2=Koehler | first2=P. G. | last3=Brenner | first3=R. J. | year=1999 | title=Comparative insecticide susceptibility and detoxification enzyme activities among pestiferous blattodea | journal=Comp Infibous Biochem Physiol C Pharmacol Toxicol Endocrinol | volume=124 | issue=3| pages=227–232 | pmid=10661713 | doi=10.1016/S0742-8413(99)00076-6 | url=http://www4.ncsu.edu/~coby/schal/1990SchalAREreview.pdf | format=PDF }}</ref><ref name=are>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1146/annurev.en.35.010190.002513 | last1=Schal | first1=C | last2=Hamilton | first2=R. L. | year=1990 | title=Integrated suppression of synanthropic cockroaches | url=http://www4.ncsu.edu/~coby/schal/1990SchalAREreview.pdf | journal=Annu. Rev. Entomol. | volume=35| pages=521–551 | pmid=2405773 }}</ref>

Cockroaches occupy a wide range of habitats. Many live in leaf litter, among the stems of matted vegetation, in rotting wood, in holes in stumps, in cavities under bark, under log piles and among debris. Some live in arid regions and have developed mechanisms to survive without access to water sources. Others are aquatic, living near the surface of water bodies, including [[Bromeliaceae|bromeliad]] [[phytotelma]]ta, and diving to forage for food. Most of these respire by piercing the water surface with the tip of the abdomen which acts as a [[snorkeling|snorkel]], but some carry a bubble of air under their thoracic shield when they submerge. Others live in the [[Canopy (biology)|forest canopy]] where they may be one of the main types of [[invertebrate]] present. Here they may hide during the day in crevices, among dead leaves, in bird and insect nests or among [[epiphyte]]s, emerging at night to feed.<ref name=Bell>{{cite book|author1=Bell, William J. |author2= Roth, Louis M.|author3= Nalepa, Christine A. |title=Cockroaches: Ecology, Behavior, and Natural History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7eVRP08kasC&pg=PA55 |year=2007 |publisher=JHU Press |isbn=978-0-8018-8616-4 |pages=55–58}}</ref>

==Behavior==
[[File:Ecdysis.jpg|thumb|upright|A cockroach soon after [[ecdysis]]]]
<!--[[File:Bush Cockroach.jpg|thumb|right|A bush cockroach (''Ellipsidion australe'')]] Purpose of this image? -->
Cockroaches are social insects; a large number of species are either gregarious or inclined to aggregate, and a slightly smaller number exhibit parental care.<ref name=Costa2006>{{cite book |author=Costa, James T. |title=The Other Insect Societies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PYRFDrZs9QAC&pg=PA148 |year=2006 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-02163-1 |page=148}}</ref> It used to be thought that cockroaches aggregated because they were reacting to environmental cues, but it is now believed that [[pheromone]]s are involved in these behaviors. Some species secrete these in their feces with gut microbial [[Symbiosis|symbionts]] being involved, while others use glands located on their mandibles. Pheromones produced by the cuticle may enable cockroaches to distinguish between different populations of cockroach by odor. The behaviors involved have only been studied in a few species, but German cockroaches leave fecal trails with an odor gradient.<ref name=Costa2006/> Other cockroaches follow such trails to discover sources of food and water, and where other cockroaches are hiding. Thus, cockroaches have [[Emergent properties|emergent behavior]], in which group or [[swarm behavior]] emerges from a simple set of individual interactions.<ref name=LihoreauEtAl2012/>

Daily rhythms may also be regulated by a complex set of hormonal controls of which only a small subset have been understood. In 2005, the role of one of these proteins, [[pigment dispersing factor]] (PDF), was isolated and found to be a key mediator in the [[circadian rhythm]]s of the cockroach.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hamasaka |first=Yasutaka |title=Chronobiological analysis and mass spectrometric characterization of pigment-dispersing factor in the cockroach Leucophaea maderae |journal=The Journal of Insect Science |date=22 December 2005|volume=5 |issue=43 |pmc=1615250 |pmid=17119625 |last2=Mohrherr |first2=C. J. |last3=Predel |first3=R. |last4=Wegener |first4=C. |page=43 |doi=10.1093/jis/5.1.43}}</ref>

Pest species adapt readily to a variety of environments, but prefer warm conditions found within buildings. Many tropical species prefer even warmer environments. Cockroaches are mainly [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]]<ref name="ucipm">{{cite web |url=http://www.ipm.ucdavis.edu/PMG/PESTNOTES/pn7467.html |title=Cockroaches |author=Rust, M. K. |date=2007 |work=University of California Integrated Pest Management Program |publisher=University of California |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> and run away when exposed to light. An exception to this is the [[Asian cockroach]], which flies mostly at night but is attracted to brightly lit surfaces and pale colors.<ref name=Richman>{{cite web |url=http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/urban/roaches/asian_cockroach.htm |title=Asian cockroach |author=Richman, Dina L. |date=1 June 2014 |work=featured Creatures |publisher=University of Florida |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>

===Collective decision-making===

Gregarious cockroaches display collective decision-making when choosing food sources. When a sufficient number of individuals (a "quorum") exploits a food source, this signals to newcomer cockroaches that they should stay there longer rather than leave for elsewhere.<ref name=LihoreauEtAl2010>{{cite journal |author1=Lihoreau, Mathieu  |author2= Deneubourg, Jean-Louis |author3= Rivault, Colette |title=Collective foraging decision in a gregarious insect|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |year=2010 |volume=64 |issue=10 |pages=1577–1587 |doi=10.1007/s00265-010-0971-7}}</ref> Other mathematical models have been developed to explain aggregation dynamics and conspecific recognition.<ref name=AmeEtAl2004>{{cite journal |author1=Ame, Jean-Marc  |author2=Rivault, Colette |author3=Deneubourg, Jean-Louis |title=Cockroach aggregation based on strain odour recognition|journal=Animal Behaviour |date=Oct 2004 |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=793–801 |doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2004.01.009}}</ref><ref name=JeansonEtAl2005>{{cite journal |author1=Jeanson, Raphael |author2=Rivault, Colette |author3=Deneubourg, Jean-Louis |author4=Blanco, Stephane |author5=Fournier, Richard |author6=Jost, Christian |author7=Theraulaz, Guy |title=Self-organized aggregation in cockroaches |journal=Animal Behaviour |date=Jan 2005 |volume=69 |issue=1 |pages=169–180 |doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2004.02.009}}</ref>

<!--http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0019748 "In group-living organisms, consensual decision of site selection results from the interplay between individual responses to site characteristics and to group-members." Paper byStéphane Canonge, Jean-Louis Deneubourg, Grégory Sempo, June 20, 2011 https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0019748-->
Cooperation and competition are balanced in cockroach group decision-making behavior.<ref name=LihoreauEtAl2012/>

Cockroaches appear to use just two pieces of information to decide where to go, namely how dark it is and how many other cockroaches there are. A study used specially-scented roach-sized [[robot]]s that appear to the roaches as real to demonstrate that once there are enough insects in a place to form a [[critical mass (sociodynamics)|critical mass]], the roaches accepted the collective decision on where to hide, even if this was an unusually light place.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1684427,00.html?imw=Y |title=Robotic Roaches Do the Trick |first=Michael D. |last=Lemonick |publisher=Time Magazine |date=15 November 2007 |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>

===Social behavior===
Gregarious German cockroaches show different behavior when reared in isolation from when reared in a group. In one study, isolated cockroaches were less likely to leave their shelters and explore, spent less time eating, interacted less with conspecifics when exposed to them, and took longer to recognize receptive females. Because these changes occurred in many contexts, the authors suggested them as constituting a [[behavioral syndrome]]. These effects might have been due either to reduced metabolic and developmental rates in isolated individuals or the fact that the isolated individuals hadn't had a training period to learn about what others were like via their antennae.<ref name=LihoreauEtAl2009>{{cite journal |author1= Lihoreau, Mathieu |author2= Brepson, Loïc|author3= Rivault, Colette |title=The weight of the clan: Even in insects, social isolation can induce a behavioural syndrome |journal=Behavioural Processes |year=2009 |volume=82 |pages=81–84 |doi=10.1016/j.beproc.2009.03.008 |pmid=19615616}}</ref>

Individual [[American cockroach]]es appear to have consistently different "personalities" regarding how they seek shelter. In addition, group personality is not simply the sum of individual choices, but reflects conformity and collective decision-making.<ref name="Planas-SitjàEtAl">{{cite journal |author1=Planas-Sitjà, Isaac |author2= Deneubourg, Jean-Louis |author3= Gibon, Céline |author4= Sempo, Grégory |title=Group personality during collective decision-making: a multi-level approach |journal=Proc. R. Soc. B |date=2015 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2014.2515 |url=https://dipot.ulb.ac.be/dspace/bitstream/2013/190793/1/Planasetal.pdf |volume=282 |pages=20142515}}</ref><ref name=Morell2015>{{cite news |last1=Morell |first1=Virginia |title=Even cockroaches have personalities |url=http://news.sciencemag.org/biology/2015/02/even-cockroaches-have-personalities|accessdate=19 February 2015 |agency=Science |date=3 February 2015 |doi=10.1126/science.aaa7797}}</ref>

The gregarious German and American cockroaches have elaborate social structure, chemical signalling, and "social herd" characteristics. Lihoreau and his fellow researchers stated:<ref name=LihoreauEtAl2012>{{cite journal |author1= Lihoreau, M. |author2=Costa, J.T. |author3=Rivault, C. |title=The social biology of domiciliary cockroaches: colony structure, kin recognition and collective decisions |journal=Insectes Sociaux |date=November 2012 |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=445–452 |doi=10.1007/s00040-012-0234-x}}</ref>

{{pull quote|1=The social biology of domiciliary cockroaches&nbsp;... can be characterized by a common shelter, overlapping generations, non-closure of groups, equal reproductive potential of group members, an absence of task specialization, high levels of social dependence, central place foraging, social information transfer, kin recognition, and a meta-population structure.<ref name=LihoreauEtAl2012/>}}

===Sounds===
Some species make a hissing noise while other cockroaches make a chirping noise. The [[Madagascar hissing cockroach]] produces its sound through the modified [[spiracle]]s on the fourth abdominal segment. Several different hisses are produced, including disturbance sounds, produced by adults and larger nymphs, and aggressive, courtship and copulatory sounds produced by adult males.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Nelson, Margaret C. |year=1979 |title=Sound production in the cockroach, ''Gromphadorhina portentosa'': The sound-producing apparatus |journal=Journal of Comparative Physiology |volume=132 |issue=1 |pages=27–38 |doi=10.1007/BF00617729 }}</ref>
''[[Henschoutedenia epilamproides]]'' has a [[Stridulation|stridulatory organ]] between its thorax and abdomen, but the purpose of the sound produced is unclear.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Guthrie, D.M. |year=1966 |title=Sound production and reception in a cockroach |journal=Journal of Experimental Biology |volume=45 |pages=321–328 |url=http://jeb.biologists.org/content/45/2/321.short }}</ref>

Several Australian species practice acoustic and vibration behavior as an aspect of courtship. They have been observed producing hisses and whistles from air forced through the spiracles. Furthermore, in the presence of a potential mate, some cockroaches tap the substrate in a rhythmic, repetitive manner. Acoustic signals may be of greater prevalence amongst perching species, particularly those that live on low vegetation in Australia's tropics.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/pid/6710.htm |title=A Guide to the Cockroaches of Australia |author1=Rentz, David |publisher=CSIRO Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-643-10320-7}}</ref>

==Biology==
===Digestive tract===
Cockroaches are generally [[Omnivore|omnivorous]]; the American cockroach (''Periplaneta americana''), for example, feeds on a great variety of foodstuffs including bread, fruit, leather, starch in book bindings, paper, glue, skin flakes, hair, dead insects and soiled clothing.<ref name=bell>{{cite book |last1=Bell |first1=William J. |last2=Adiyodi |first2=K. G. |title=American Cockroach |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7JCsYtH-VcYC&pg=PA4 |year=1981 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-412-16140-7 |page=4}}</ref> Many species of cockroach harbor [[Symbiosis|symbiotic]] [[protozoa]]ns and [[bacteria]] in their gut which are able to digest cellulose. In many species, these symbionts may be essential if the insect is to utilize cellulose; however, some species secrete [[cellulase]] in their [[saliva]], and the wood-eating cockroach, ''[[Panesthia cribrata]]'', is able to survive indefinitely on a diet of crystallized cellulose while being free of micro-organisms.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Slaytor, Michael |year=1992 |title=Cellulose digestion in termites and cockroaches: What role do symbionts play? |journal=Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology B |volume=103 |issue=4 |pages=775–784 |doi=10.1016/0305-0491(92)90194-V}}</ref>

The similarity of these symbionts in the genus ''[[Cryptocercus]]'' to those in termites are such that these cockroaches have been suggested to be more closely related to termites than to other cockroaches,<ref>{{cite journal |author=Eggleton, P. |year=2001 |title=Termites and trees: a review of recent advances in termite phylogenetics |journal= Insectes Sociaux |volume=48 |pages=187–193 |doi=10.1007/PL00001766 |issue=3}}</ref> and current research strongly supports this hypothesis about their relationships.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/reprint/20/6/907.pdf |title=Evidence for Cocladogenesis Between Diverse Dictyopteran Lineages and Their Intracellular Endosymbionts |doi=10.1093/molbev/msg097 |year=2003 |last1=Lo |first1=N. |journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution |volume=20 |issue=6 |pages=907–13 |pmid=12716997 |last2=Bandi |first2=C. |last3=Watanabe |first3=H. |last4=Nalepa |first4=C. |last5=Beninati |first5=T. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/1312834505048387?url=http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/20/6/907.full.pdf |archivedate=8 August 2011 |df= }}</ref> All species studied so far carry the obligate [[Mutualism (biology)|mutualistic]] endosymbiont bacterium ''[[Blattabacterium]]'', with the exception of ''[[Nocticola australiensise]]'', an Australian cave-dwelling species without eyes, pigment or wings, which recent genetic studies indicate is a very primitive cockroach.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cave may hold missing link |author=Leung, Chee Chee |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/cave-may-hold-missing-link/2007/03/21/1174153159560.html |newspaper=The Age |date=22 March 2007 |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=Beninati>{{cite journal |pmid=17376757 |year=2007 |last1=Lo |first1=N. |last2=Beninati|first2=T |last3=Stone |first3=F. |last4=Walker |first4=J. |last5=Sacchi |first5=L. |title=Cockroaches that lack ''Blattabacterium'' endosymbionts: The phylogenetically divergent genus ''Nocticola'' |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=327–30 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2006.0614 |pmc=2464682 |journal=Biology Letters}}</ref> It had previously been thought that all five families of cockroach were descended from a common ancestor that was infected with ''B. cuenoti''. It may be that ''N. australiensise'' subsequently lost its symbionts, or alternatively this hypothesis will need to be re-examined.<ref name=Beninati/>

===Tracheae and breathing===

Like other insects, cockroaches breathe through a system of tubes called [[Invertebrate trachea|tracheae]] which are attached to openings called [[spiracle]]s on all body segments. When the [[carbon dioxide]] level in the insect rises high enough, valves on the spiracles open and carbon dioxide [[Diffusion|diffuses]] out and [[oxygen]] diffuses in. The tracheal system branches repeatedly, the finest tracheoles bringing air directly to each [[cell (biology)|cell]], allowing gaseous exchange to take place.<ref name=Umass>{{cite web |url=http://www.bio.umass.edu/biology/kunkel/cockroach_faq.html#Q21 |title=The Cockroach FAQ |publisher=University of Massachusetts |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>

While cockroaches do not have [[lung]]s as do [[vertebrate]]s, and can continue to respire if their heads are removed, in some very large species, the body musculature may contract rhythmically to forcibly move air in and out of the spiracles; this may be considered a form of breathing.<ref name=Umass/>

===Reproduction===
Cockroaches use [[pheromone]]s to attract mates, and the males practice courtship rituals, such as posturing and [[stridulation]]. Like many insects, cockroaches mate facing away from each other with their genitalia in contact, and copulation can be prolonged. A few species are known to be [[parthenogenesis|parthenogenetic]], reproducing without the need for males.<ref name=IIBD/>

Female cockroaches are sometimes seen carrying egg cases on the end of their abdomens; the German cockroach holds about 30 to 40 long, thin eggs in a case called an [[ootheca]]. She drops the capsule prior to hatching, though live births do occur in rare instances. The egg capsule may take more than five hours to lay and is initially bright white in color. The eggs are hatched from the combined pressure of the hatchlings gulping air. The hatchlings are initially bright white [[nymph (biology)|nymphs]] and continue inflating themselves with air, becoming harder and darker within about four hours. Their transient white stage while hatching and later while [[ecdysis|molting]] has led to claims of [[albino]] cockroaches.<ref name=IIBD/> Development from eggs to adults takes three to four months. Cockroaches live up to a year, and the female may produce up to eight egg cases in a lifetime; in favorable conditions, she can produce 300 to 400 offspring. Other species of cockroaches, however, can produce far more eggs; in some cases a female needs to be impregnated only once to be able to lay eggs for the rest of her life.<ref name=IIBD/>

The female usually attaches the egg case to a substrate, inserts it into a suitably protective crevice, or carries it about until just before the eggs hatch. Some species, however, are [[ovoviviparous]], keeping the eggs inside their body, with or without an egg case, until they hatch. At least one genus, ''[[Diploptera]]'', is fully [[viviparous]].<ref name=IIBD/>

Cockroaches have [[incomplete metamorphosis]], meaning that the [[nymph (biology)|nymphs]] are generally similar to the adults, except for undeveloped wings and genitalia. Development is generally slow, and may take a few months to over a year. The adults are also long-lived, and have survived for as much as four years in the laboratory.<ref name=IIBD/>

