===Hardiness===
Cockroaches are among the hardiest insects. Some species are capable of remaining active for a month without food and are able to survive on limited resources, such as the glue from the back of postage stamps.<ref name='M & V E'>{{cite book |editor1-last=Mullen |editor1-first=Gary |editor2-last=Durden |editor2-first=Lance |title=Medical and Veterinary Entomology |year= 2002 |publisher = Academic Press |location = Amsterdam |isbn=0-12-510451-0 |page=32}}</ref> Some can go without air for 45 minutes. [[Japanese cockroach]] (''Periplaneta japonica'') nymphs, which [[hibernate]] in cold winters, survived twelve hours at −5&nbsp;°C to −8&nbsp;°C in laboratory experiments.<ref name=Tanaka1997>{{cite journal |last1=Tanaka |first1=K. |last2=Tanaka |first2=S. |title=Winter Survival and Freeze Tolerance in a Northern Cockroach, ''Periplaneta japonica'' (Blattidae: Dictyoptera)|journal=Zoological Science |date=1997 |volume=14 |issue=5 |pages=849–853 |doi=10.2108/zsj.14.849 |url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/110003323491}}</ref>

Experiments on decapitated specimens of several species of cockroach found a variety of behavioral functionality remained, including shock avoidance and escape behavior, although many insects other than cockroaches are also able to survive decapitation, and popular claims of the longevity of headless cockroaches do not appear to be based on published research.<ref name=berenbaum2009>{{cite book|last=Berenbaum|first=May|title=The Earwig's Tail: A Modern Bestiary of Multi-legged Legends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FOlpPl_15csC&pg=PA53|date=30 September 2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03540-9|pages=53–54}}</ref><ref name=choi2007/> The severed head is able to survive and wave its antennae for several hours, or longer when refrigerated and given nutrients.<ref name=choi2007>{{cite news | title= Fact or fiction?: a cockroach can live without its head | first=Charles | last=Choi | work=Scientific American | date=15 March 2007 | publisher=Scientific American | url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=fact-or-fiction-cockroach-can-live-without-head | accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref>

It is [[urban legend|popularly suggested]] that cockroaches will "inherit the earth" if humanity destroys itself in a [[nuclear warfare|nuclear war]]. Cockroaches do indeed have a much higher radiation resistance than [[vertebrate]]s, with the lethal dose perhaps six to 15 times that for humans. However, they are not exceptionally radiation-resistant compared to other insects, such as the [[Drosophila melanogaster|fruit fly]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/k2/moments/s1567313.htm |author=Kruszelnicki, Karl S. |date=23 February 2006 |title=Cockroaches and Radiation |publisher=ABC Science |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>

The cockroach's ability to withstand radiation better than human beings can be explained through the cell cycle. Cells are most vulnerable to the effects of radiation when they are dividing. A cockroach's cells divide only once each time it molts, which is weekly at most in a juvenile roach. Since not all cockroaches would be molting at the same time, many would be unaffected by an acute burst of radiation, although lingering radioactive fallout would still be harmful.<ref name=Umass/>

==Relationship with humans==

[[File:"Periplaneta americana" connected to the electrophysiology equipment.JPG|thumb|Cockroaches in research: ''Periplaneta americana'' in an [[electrophysiology]] experiment]]

===In research and education===
Because of their ease of rearing and resilience, cockroaches have been used as insect models in the laboratory, particularly in the fields of [[neurobiology]], [[reproductive physiology]] and [[social behavior]].<ref name=Costa2006/> The cockroach is a convenient insect to study as it is large and simple to raise in a laboratory environment. This makes it suitable both for research and for school and undergraduate biology studies. It can be used in experiments on topics such as learning, sexual [[pheromone]]s, spatial orientation, [[aggression]], activity rhythms and the [[Circadian clock|biological clock]], and behavioral ecology.<ref name="Bell2012">{{cite book |last=Bell |first=W. J. |title=The Laboratory Cockroach: Experiments in cockroach anatomy, physiology and behavior |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2gkjBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 |date=2012 |origyear=1981 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-94-011-9726-7}}</ref> Research conducted in 2014 suggests that humans fear cockroaches the most, even more than mosquitoes, due to an evolutionary aversion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20140918-the-reality-about-roaches|title=Cockroaches: The insect we are programmed to fear|date=18 September 2014|work=BBC}}</ref>

===As pests===

The Blattodea include some thirty species of cockroaches associated with humans; these species are atypical of the thousands of species in the order.<ref name=GullanCranston>{{cite book|last1=Gullan |first1=P. J. |last2=Cranston |first2=P. S. |title=The Insects: An Outline of Entomology |date=2014 |publisher=Wiley |isbn=978-1-118-84615-5 |page=508}}</ref> They feed on human and pet food and can leave an offensive odor.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Brenner | first1=R.J. | last2=Koehler | first2=P. | last3=Patterson | first3=R.S. | year=1987 | title=Health Implications of Cockroach Infestations | journal=Infestations in Med | volume=4 | issue=8| pages=349–355 }}</ref> They can passively transport [[pathogen]]ic microbes on their body surfaces, particularly in environments such as hospitals.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1017/S0950268800068254 | last1=Rivault | first1=C. | last2=Cloarec | first2=A. | last3=Guyader | first3=A. Le | year=1993 | title=Bacterial load of cockroaches in relation to urban environment| journal=Epidemiology and Infection | volume=110 | issue=2| pages=317–325 | pmid=8472775 | pmc=2272268 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1179/136485906X78463 | last1=Elgderi | first1=R.M. | last2=Ghenghesh | first2=K.S. | last3=Berbash | first3=N. | year=2006 | title=Carriage by the German cockroach (''Blattella germanica'') of multiple-antibiotic-resistant bacteria that are potentially pathogenic to humans, in hospitals and households in Tripoli, Libya | journal=Ann Trop Med Parasitol | volume=100 | issue=1| pages=55–62 | pmid=16417714 }}</ref> Cockroaches are linked with allergic reactions in humans.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Bernton | first1=H.S. | last2=Brown | first2=H. | year=1964 | title=Insect Allergy Preliminary Studies of the Cockroach | journal=J. Allergy | volume=35 | issue=506–513 |pmid=14226309 | pages=506–13 | doi=10.1016/0021-8707(64)90082-6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Kutrup | first1=B | year=2003 | title=Cockroach Infestation in Some Hospitals in Trabzon, Turkey | url=http://journals.tubitak.gov.tr/zoology/issues/zoo-03-27-1/zoo-27-1-12-0005-1.pdf | journal=Turk. J. Zool. | volume=27 | pages=73–77 }}</ref> One of the proteins that trigger allergic reactions is [[tropomyosin]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/S0091-6749(99)70375-1 | last1=Santos | first1=A. B. | last2=Chapman | first2=M. D. | last3=Aalberse | first3=R. C. | last4=Vailes | first4=L. D. | last5=Ferriani | first5=V. P. | last6=Oliver | first6=C. | last7=Rizzo | first7=M. C. | last8=Naspitz | first8=C. K. | last9=Arruda | first9=L. K. | displayauthors=8 | year=1999 | title=Cockroach allergens and asthma in Brazil: identification of tropomyosin as a major allergen with potential cross-reactivity with mite and shrimp allergens | journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology | volume=104 | issue=2| pages=329–337 | pmid=10452753}}</ref> These allergens are also linked with [[asthma]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/0091-6749(79)90196-9 | last1=Kang | first1=B. | last2=Vellody | first2=D. | last3=Homburger | first3=H. | last4=Yunginger | first4=J. W. | year=1979 | title=Cockroach cause of allergic asthma. Its specificity and immunologic profile | journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology | volume=63 | issue=2| pages=80–86 | pmid=83332}}</ref> About 60% of asthma patients in [[Chicago]] are also sensitive to cockroach allergens.  Studies similar to this have been done globally and all the results are similar.  Cockroaches can live for a few days up to a month without food, so just because no cockroaches are visible in a home does not mean they are not there. Approximately 20-48% of homes with no visible sign of cockroaches have detectable cockroach allergens in dust.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Eggleston|first=P.A. |last2=Arruda|first2=L.K.|date=2001 |title=Ecology and elimination of cockroaches and allergens in the home.|doi=10.1067/mai.2001.113671|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology |volume=107 |pages=S422–S429}}</ref>

Cockroaches can burrow into human ears, causing pain and hearing loss.<ref name="guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2017/nov/10/cockroach-stuck-in-my-ear|title=Experience: A cockroach got stuck in my ear|first=Hendrik|last=Helmer|date=10 November 2017|accessdate=10 November 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/10/cockroach-australian-mans-ear-hendrik-helmer_n_4576128.html|title=Doctors Pull Cockroach From Australian Man's Ear (PHOTO)|date=10 January 2014|website=Huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=10 November 2017|via=Huff Post}}</ref> They may be removed with forceps, possibly after first drowning with [[olive oil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/doctor-pulls-2cm-long-cockroach-from-hendrik-helmers-ear-9052158.html|title=Doctor pulls 2cm long cockroach from Hendrik Helmer's ear|date=10 January 2014|website=Independent.co.uk|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2014/01/10/3923531.htm|title=Man has 2cm cockroach removed from ear|date=10 January 2014|website=Abc.net.au|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/priya-malhotra/cockroach-in-ear_b_934269.html|title=The Common Ailment of Cockroach-in-Ear|first=Priya|last=Malhotra|date=23 August 2011|website=Huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref>

====Control====
Many remedies have been tried in the search for control of the major pest species of cockroaches, which are resilient and fast-breeding. Household chemicals like [[sodium bicarbonate]] (baking soda) have been suggested, without evidence for their effectiveness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://homeremediesandtips.whw1.com/home/pests/6-top-home-remedies-to-kill-and-control-cockroaches#BakingSoda |title=Best Home Remedies To Kill And Control Cockroaches – Baking Soda |website=HRT.whw1.com |accessdate=2015-06-20}}</ref> Garden herbs including  [[bay leaves|bay]], [[catnip]], [[Mentha|mint]], [[cucumber]], and [[garlic]] have been proposed as repellents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://homeremediesandtips.whw1.com/home/pests/6-top-home-remedies-to-kill-and-control-cockroaches#Catnip |title=Best Home Remedies To Kill And Control Cockroaches – Catnip |website=HRT.whw1.com |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> Poisoned bait containing [[hydramethylnon]] or [[fipronil]], and [[boric acid]] powder is effective on adults.<ref name="alamance">{{cite web |url=http://www.alamance-nc.com/Alamance-NC/Departments/Environmental+Health/Environmental+Hazards/Cockroaches.htm |title=Cockroaches |publisher=[[Alamance County]] Department of Environmental Health |accessdate=11 May 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312045904/http://www.alamance-nc.com/Alamance-NC/Departments/Environmental%2BHealth/Environmental%2BHazards/Cockroaches.htm |archivedate=March 12, 2009 |df= }}</ref> Baits with egg killers are also quite effective at reducing the cockroach population. Alternatively, insecticides containing [[deltamethrin]] or [[pyrethrin]] are very effective.<ref name="alamance" /> In Singapore and Malaysia, taxi drivers use [[Pandanus amaryllifolius|pandan]] leaves to repel cockroaches in their vehicles.<ref>Li J. and Ho S.H. [http://www.ntu.edu.sg/eee/urop/congress2003/Proceedings/abstract/NUS_FoS/TDP%20USP/Li%20Jingmei.pdf Pandan leaves (''Pandanus amaryllifolius'' Roxb.) As A Natural Cockroach Repellent]. ''Proceedings of the 9th National Undergraduate Research Opportunities Programme'' (13 September 2003).</ref>

Few parasites and predators are effective for [[biological control]] of cockroaches. [[Parasitoid]]al [[wasp]]s such as ''[[Ampulex]]'' wasps sting nerve ganglia in the cockroach's [[thorax]], temporarily paralyzing the victim, allowing the wasp to deliver an incapacitating sting into the cockroach's brain. The wasp clips the antennae with its mandibles and drinks some [[hemolymph]] before dragging the prey to a burrow, where an egg (rarely two) is laid on it<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Paterson Fox |first1=Eduardo Gonçalves |last2=Bressan-Nascimento |first2=Suzete |last3=Eizemberg |first3=Roberto |title=Notes on the Biology and Behaviour of the Jewel Wasp, Ampulex compressa (Fabricius, 1781) (Hymenoptera; Ampulicidae), in the Laboratory, Including First Record of Gregarious Reproduction |journal=Entomological News |date=September 2009 |volume=120 |issue=4 |pages=430–437 |doi=10.3157/021.120.0412}}</ref>. The wasp larva feeds on the subdued living cockroach.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fox |first1=Eduardo G P |last2=BUYS |first2=SANDOR CRISTIANO |last3=MALLET |first3=JACE-NIR REIS DOS SANTOS |last4=BRESSAN-NASCIMENTO |first4=SUZETE |title=On the morphology of the juvenile stages of Ampulex compressa (Fabricius 1781) (Hymenoptera, Ampulicidae) |journal=Zootaxa |date=3 August 2006 |volume=1279 |issue=1 |pages=43 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.1279.1.2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | authorlink=Ross Piper |author=Piper, Ross |year=2007 |title=Extraordinary Animals: An Encyclopedia of Curious and Unusual Animals |publisher=[[Greenwood Press (publisher)|Greenwood Press]] |pages= }}</ref> Another wasp which is considered a promising candidate for biological control is the ensign wasp ''[[Evania appendigaster]]'' which attacks cockroach oothecae to lay a single egg inside. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Fox |first1=Eduardo G P |title=Evania appendigaster Development |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0iGF5P3td9k |website=YouTube |date=10 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fox |first1=Eduardo Gonçalves Paterson |last2=Solis |first2=Daniel Russ |last3=Rossi |first3=Mônica Lanzoni |last4=Eizemberg |first4=Roberto |last5=Taveira |first5=Luiz Pilize |last6=Bressan-Nascimento |first6=Suzete |title=The preimaginal stages of the ensign wasp Evania appendigaster (Hymenoptera, Evaniidae), a cockroach egg predator |journal=Invertebrate Biology |date=June 2012 |volume=131 |issue=2 |pages=133–143 |doi=10.1111/j.1744-7410.2012.00261.x |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260099527_The_preimaginal_stages_of_the_ensign_wasp_Evania_appendigaster_Hymenoptera_Evaniidae_a_cockroach_egg_predator |language=en}}</ref> Ongoing research is still developing technologies allowing for mass-rearing these wasps for application releases. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bressan-Nascimento |first1=S. |last2=Oliveira |first2=D.M.P. |last3=Fox |first3=E.G.P. |title=Thermal requirements for the embryonic development of Periplaneta americana (L.) (Dictyoptera: Blattidae) with potential application in mass-rearing of egg parasitoids |journal=Biological Control |date=December 2008 |volume=47 |issue=3 |pages=268–272 |doi=10.1016/j.biocontrol.2008.09.001}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bressan-Nascimento |first1=S. |last2=Fox |first2=E.G.P. |last3=Pilizi |first3=L.G.T. |title=Effects of different temperatures on the life history of Evania appendigaster L. (Hymenoptera: Evaniidae), a solitary oothecal parasitoid of Periplaneta americana L. (Dictyoptera: Blattidae) |journal=Biological Control |date=February 2010 |volume=52 |issue=2 |pages=104–109 |doi=10.1016/j.biocontrol.2009.10.005}}</ref>

{{Anchor|Vegas roach trap}}Cockroaches can be trapped in a deep, smooth-walled jar baited with food inside, placed so that cockroaches can reach the opening, for example with a ramp of card or twigs on the outside. An inch or so of water or stale beer (by itself a cockroach attractant) in the jar can be used to drown any insects thus captured. The method works well with the American cockroach, but less so with the German cockroach.<ref>{{cite book |author=Herms, William Brodbeck |title=Medical and Veterinary Entomology |publisher=MacMillan |year=1915 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SWsoAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA44 |page=44}}</ref>

=== As food ===
{{See also|Entomophagy|Cockroach farming}}
Although considered disgusting in [[Western culture]], cockroaches are eaten in many places around the world.<ref name=Copeland>Marion Copeland [2004]. [https://books.google.ca/books?id=MNQSAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA88&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q&f=false Cockroach] (Pages 86 to 88). Published by Reaktion Books</ref><ref>Ronald L. Taylor, Barbara J. Carter [1976]. [https://books.google.ca/books?id=OgJ8PQAACAAJ&dq=the+original+guide+to+insect+cookery&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpvILvjurQAhUD3GMKHScPAQ0Q6AEIHDAA Entertaining with Insects: Or, The Original Guide to Insect Cookery]. Published by Woodbridge Press Publishing Company.</ref> Whereas household pest cockroaches may carry bacteria and viruses, cockroaches bred under laboratory conditions can be used to prepare nutritious food.<ref>David George Gordon [1998]. [https://books.google.ca/books?id=i0Mcxow-66QC&dq=Cockroach+Á+La+King&hl=en&sa=X The Eat-a-bug Cookbook] (Page 78). Published by Ten Speed Press.</ref>  In Mexico and Thailand, the heads and legs are removed, and the remainder may be boiled, sautéed, grilled, dried or diced.<ref name=Copeland/> In [[China]], cockroaches have become popular as medicine and cockroach farming is rising with over 100 farms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Demick|first1=Barbara|title=Cockroach farms multiplying in China|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-c1-china-cockroach-20131015-dto-htmlstory.html|accessdate=20 April 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=15 October 2013}}</ref> The cockroaches are fried twice in a [[wok]] of hot oil, which makes them crispy with soft innards that are like [[cottage cheese]].<ref>Malcolm Moore [2013]. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/10399940/How-to-eat-a-cockroach-a-Telegraph-guide.html How to eat a cockroach: a Telegraph guide]. Published by Washington Post.</ref><ref>[2015]. [https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-34517443 How cockroaches could save lives]. Published by BBC News.</ref> Fried cockroaches are ground and sold as pills for stomach, heart and liver diseases.<ref>David McKenzie [2014]. [http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/31/travel/china-cockroach-farming-food/ Eating cockroaches in China: Healing and delicious?]. Published by CNN.</ref> A cockroach recipe from [[Taiwan|Formosa]] (Taiwan) specifies salting and frying cockroaches after removing the head and entrails.<ref name=papers>Richard Schweid [2015]. [https://books.google.ca/books?id=K4ZoCQAAQBAJ&lpg=PT69&dq=cockroach%20recipe&pg=PT69#v=onepage&q=cockroach%20recipe&f=false The Cockroach Papers: A Compendium of History and Lore] (Page 69). Published by University of Chicago Press.</ref>

===In traditional and homeopathic medicine===

In China, cockroaches are raised in large quantities for medicinal purposes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chen |first=Stephen |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2142316/giant-indoor-farm-china-breeding-six-billion-cockroaches-year |title=A giant indoor farm in China is breeding 6 billion cockroaches a year. Here's why |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=2018-04-19 |accessdate=2018-04-20 }}</ref>

Two species of cockroach were used in [[homeopathic medicine]] in the 19th century.<ref name="Kmietowicz1997">{{cite journal | last=Kmietowicz | first=Z. | title=Cockroaches blamed for high asthma rates | journal=BMJ | volume=314 | issue=7092 | date=1997-05-17 | doi=10.1136/bmj.314.7092.1433i | pages=i–i}}</ref>

===Conservation===
{{See also|Depopulation of cockroaches in post-Soviet states}}
While a small minority of cockroaches are associated with human habitats and viewed as repugnant by many people, a few species are of conservation concern. The Lord Howe Island wood-feeding cockroach (''[[Panesthia lata]]'') is listed as endangered by the [[New South Wales]] Scientific Committee, but the cockroach may be extinct on [[Lord Howe Island]] itself. The introduction of rats, the spread of Rhodes grass (''[[Chloris gayana]]'') and fires are possible reasons for their scarcity.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lord Howe Island wood-feeding cockroach – endangered species listing |url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/determinations/PanesthiaLataEndangeredDeclaration.htm |work=Office of Environment and Heritage |publisher=Government of New South Wales |accessdate=10 November 2015 |date=2011}}</ref> Two species are currently listed as [[Endangered species|endangered]] and [[critically endangered]] by the [[IUCN]] Red List, ''[[Delosia ornata]]'' and ''[[Nocticola gerlachi]]''.<ref name=IUCN2012>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gerlach | first1 = J. | title = ''Delosia ornata'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 2012 | page = e.T199490A2593559 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 2012 | url = http://oldredlist.iucnredlist.org/details/199490/0 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012.RLTS.T199490A2593559.en | access-date = 6 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=IUCN20122>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gerlach | first1 = J. | title = ''Nocticola gerlachi'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 2012 | page = e.T199508A2595807 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 2012 | url = http://oldredlist.iucnredlist.org/details/199508/0 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012.RLTS.T199508A2595807.en | access-date = 6 January 2018}}</ref> Both cockroaches have a restricted distribution and are threatened by habitat loss and rising sea levels. Only 600 ''Delosia ornata'' adults and 300 nymphs are known to exist, and these are threatened by a hotel development. No action has been taken to save the two cockroach species, but protecting their natural habitats may prevent their extinction. In the former Soviet Union, cockroach populations have been declining at an alarming rate; this may be exaggerated, or the phenomenon may be temporary or cyclic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Исчезновение тараканов на Белгородчине не связано с радиацией |url=http://www.bel.ru/news/2006/12/04/21613.html |accessdate=24 November 2015 |work=Bel.ru |date=4 December 2006 |language=Russian}}</ref> One species of roach, ''[[Simandoa conserfariam]]'' is considered [[extinct in the wild]].

===In culture===
{{main|Cockroaches in popular culture}}
[[File:Roachies.JPG|thumb|[[Madagascar hissing cockroach]]es kept as pets]]
Cockroaches were known and considered repellent but useful in medicines in [[Classical times]]. An insect named in Greek "σίλφη" (''silphe'') has been identified with the cockroach. It is mentioned by [[Aristotle]], saying that it sheds its skin; it is described as foul-smelling in [[Aristophanes]]' play ''[[Peace (play)|Peace]]''; [[Euenus]] called it a pest of book collections, being "page-eating, destructive, black-bodied" in his ''Analect''. [[Virgil]] named the cockroach "Lucifuga" ("one that avoids light"). [[Pliny the Elder]] recorded the use of "Blatta" in various medicines; he describes the insect as disgusting, and as seeking out dark corners to avoid the light.<ref name=Smith>{{cite book |last=Anthon |first=Charles |editor=Smith, William |title=A Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=30LCBp71dBsC&pg=PA161 |edition=3rd American |year=1843 |publisher=American Book Company |location=New York – Cincinnati – Chicago |page=161}}</ref><ref name="Lockyer1871">{{cite book |last=Lockyer |first= Norman |title=Nature |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vrdCAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA27 |year=1871 |publisher=Macmillan Journals |page=27}}</ref> [[Pedanius Dioscorides|Dioscorides]] recorded the use of the "Silphe", ground up with oil, as a remedy for earache.<ref name="Lockyer1871"/>

[[Lafcadio Hearn]] (1850–1904) asserted that "For [[tetanus]]<!--sic, no comma--> cockroach tea is given. I do not know how many cockroaches go to make up the cup; but I find that faith in this remedy is strong among many of the American population of New Orleans. A poultice of boiled cockroaches is placed over the wound." He adds that cockroaches are eaten, fried with garlic, for indigestion.<ref name="HearnStarr2001">{{cite book |last1=Hearn |first1=Lafcadio |last2=Starr |first2=S. Frederick |title=Inventing New Orleans: Writings of Lafcadio Hearn |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H8Y6GZW483cC&pg=PA68 |year=2001 |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=978-1-57806-353-6 |pages=68–69}}</ref>

Several cockroach species, such as ''[[Blaptica dubia]]'', are raised as food for insectivorous pets.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wu |first1=Hao| last2=Appel |first2=Arthur G. |last3=Hu |first3=Xing Ping |title=Instar Determination of ''Blaptica dubia'' (Blattodea: Blaberidae) Using Gaussian Mixture Models |journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America |volume=106 |issue=3 |year=2013| pages=323–328 |issn=0013-8746| doi=10.1603/AN12131}}</ref> A few cockroach species are raised as pets, most commonly the giant [[Madagascar hissing cockroach]], ''Gromphadorhina portentosa''.<ref>{{cite web |author=Mulder, Phil |title=Madagascar Hissing Cockroaches: Information and Care |publisher=Oklahoma 4-H Youth Development. Oklahoma State University |accessdate=31 October 2013 |url=http://agweb.okstate.edu/fourh/aitc/lessons/extras/cockroach.pdf}}</ref>  Whilst the hissing cockroaches may be the most commonly kept species, there are many species that are kept by cockroach enthusiasts; there is even a specialist society: the Blattodea Culture Group (BCG), which was a thriving organisation for about 15 years although now appears to be dormant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blattodea-culture-group.org/|title=Blattodea Culture Group|website=Blattodea-culture-group.org|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref>  The BCG provided a source of literature for people interested in rearing cockroaches which was otherwise limited to either scientific papers, or general insect books, or books covering a variety of exotic pets; in the absence of an inclusive book one member published ''Introduction to Rearing Cockroaches'' which still appears to be the only book dedicated to rearing cockroaches.<ref>Bragg, P.E. (1997) ''An Introduction to Rearing Cockroaches.'' P.E. Bragg, Ilkeston.</ref>

Cockroaches have been used for space tests. A cockroach given the name [[Nadezhda (cockroach)|Nadezhda]] was sent into space by Russian scientists as part of a [[Foton (satellite)#Foton-M|Foton-M]] mission, during which she mated, and later became the first terrestrial animal to produce offspring that had been conceived in space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.ria.ru/science/20071023/85202812.html |title="Hope" the Russian cockroach gives birth to first space babies |work=RIA Novosti |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>

Because of their long association with humans, cockroaches are frequently referred to in popular culture. In Western culture, cockroaches are often depicted as dirty pests.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/1534650106288965 |title=Graded Exposure Therapy for Long-Standing Disgust-Related Cockroach Avoidance in an Older Male |year=2007 |last1=Berle |first1=D. |journal=Clinical Case Studies |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=339–347}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1089/cpb.2005.8.162 |title=Mixing Realities? An Application of Augmented Reality for the Treatment of Cockroach Phobia |year=2005 |last1=Botella |first1=C.M. |last2=Juan |first2=M. C. |last3=Baños |first3=R. M. |last4=Alcañiz |first4=M. |last5=Guillén |first5=V. |last6=Rey |first6=B. |journal=CyberPsychology & Behavior |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=162–171}}</ref> In a 1750–1752 journal, Peter Osbeck noted that cockroaches were frequently seen and found their way to the bakeries, after the sailing ship ''Gothenburg'' ran aground and was destroyed by rocks.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Klausnitzer |first1=B. |title=Insects: their biology and cultural history |date=1987 |publisher=Universe Books |location=New York |isbn=978-0-87663-666-4 |page=42}}</ref>

[[Donald Harington (writer)|Donald Harington's]] satirical novel ''[[The Cockroaches of Stay More]]'' (Harcourt, 1989) imagines a community of "roosterroaches" in a mythical Ozark town where the insects are named after their human counterparts. [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] has famously quoted, "I am a survivor. I am like a cockroach, you just can't get rid of me."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thinkexist.com/quotation/i_am_a_survivor-i_am_like_a_cockroach-you_just/333818.html |title=Madonna |quote=I am a survivor. I am like a cockroach, you just can't get rid of me |author=Madonna |website=Thinkexist.com |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> An [[urban legend]] maintains that cockroaches are [[immortality|immortal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cockroaches are not radiation-proof and most are not pests |url=http://www.bbc.com/earth/story/20160926-cockroaches-are-not-radiation-proof-and-most-are-not-pests |accessdate=1 June 2018 |publisher=BBC Earth}}</ref>

