{{other uses|A Man Alone (disambiguation)}} The '''man alone''' is a literary [[stock character]]. Usually an [[antihero]], he is similar to the [[Byronic hero]]. The man alone tends to epitomise [[existentialism]], and, in the words of the academic E. H. McCormick is "the solitary, rootless nonconformist, who in a variety of forms crops up persistently in New Zealand writing".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otago.ac.nz/deepsouth/1198/MenAlone.html |title=Men Alone |publisher=Otago.ac.nz |date= |accessdate=2015-06-06}}</ref>
Men alone figure frequently in the literature of newly settled or recently colonised countries such as [[Australian literature|Australia]] and especially [[New Zealand literature|New Zealand]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://researchspace.auckland.ac.nz/handle/2292/10203 |title=The Man Alone, the Black Sheep and the Bad Apple: Squeaky Wheels of New Zealand Cinema |publisher=Researchspace.auckland.ac.nz |date= |accessdate=2015-06-06}}</ref> and the term is likely to have found popularity with the publication of the "Great Kiwi Novel", ''[[Man Alone]]'' by [[John Mulgan]] in 1939 (this novel's title itself originated in a quotation from [[Ernest Hemingway]]'s ''[[To Have and Have Not (novel)|To Have and Have Not]]'').<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/Writers/Profiles/Mulgan,%20John |title=New Zealand Book Council |publisher=Bookcouncil.org.nz |date= |accessdate=2015-06-06}}</ref> The man alone is, by nature, a [[loner]], either by choice or as a result of circumstances beyond his control. This state of separation from society is often literal, in that the man alone will often live physically separate from society as a hermit or working in the wilds of the country. At other times, the state is psychological only; the man alone may live within the presence of others but be emotionally separate or aloof from them.
The sense of physical or psychological separation between the man alone and society often results in the man alone facing interactions with authority which become [[kafkaesque]] through mutual misunderstanding.
==Examples of the man alone in literature and film== *Johnson, in ''[[Man Alone]]'', by [[John Mulgan]] *John Hobson, in ''[[The Quiet Earth]]'', by [[Craig Harrison (writer)|Craig Harrison]] *Smith in ''[[Sleeping Dogs (film)|Sleeping Dogs]]'', based on ''Smith's Dream'' by [[C. K. Stead]] *[[Max Rockatansky]] in the [[Mad Max]] series. *The Sniper in [[Team Fortress 2#Support|Team Fortress 2]]
